<div id="search-tips">
	<div class="col-left">
		<h2>Advanced Search Methods</h2>
		<p>The five search methods are:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>
				<b>Word Search (or)</b><br>
				<a href="/search?q=americans%20working" class="example">americans working</a>
				This searches for any tweets with either <span class="word">americans</span> <u>or</u> <span class="word">working</span>.<br>
				› Words are stemmed: variations of the same word will be included (eg. America, work, works, worked, etc.)<br>
				› Common words are ignored (eg. the, on, for, etc.)
			</li>
			<li>
				<b>Phrase Search (and)</b>
				<a href='/search?q="americans working"%20"jobs"' class="example">"americans working" "jobs"</a>
				This looks for tweets with the exact phrases <span class="word">"americans working"</span> <u>and</u> <span class="word">"jobs"</span>.<br>
				› Phrases need to consist of full words.
			</li>
			<li>
				<b>Exact Search</b>
				<a href="/search?q==notadoctor=" class="example">=notadoctor=</a>
				This looks for exact letter combinations even within words. You won't need this much.<br>
				› Compare <a class="word" href='/search?q="notadoctor"'>"notadoctor"</a> vs <a class="word" href="/search?q==notadoctor=">=notadoctor=</a>.<br>
				› When combined, it functions as an <u>or</u> search.
			</li>
			<li>
				<b>Label Search</b>
				<a href="/search?q=::obama%20::biden" class="example">#obama #biden</a>
				This looks for all tweets with the labels <span class="word">#obama</span> <u>or</u> <span class="word">#biden</span>.<br>
				<br>
				<a href="/search?q=::obama!%20::biden!" class="example">#obama! #biden!</a>
				This looks for all tweets with the labels <span class="word">#obama</span> <u>and</u> <span class="word">#biden</span>.<br>
				› Command-clicking a label will AND-search for this label.<br>
				<br>
				<a href="/search?q=::obama!%20::biden!%20::iran%20::china" class="example">#obama! #biden! #iran #china</a>
				This looks for all tweets with the labels <span class="word">#obama</span> <u>and</u> <span class="word">#biden</span>, plus <span class="word">#iran</span> <u>or</u> <span class="word">#china</span>.
			</li>
			<li>
				<b>RegEx Search</b>
				<a href="/search?q=%2F#\b\w+\b%2F" class="example">/#\b\w+\b/gi</a>
				If you're familiar with regular expressions, this is a powerful way to search for patterns.<br>
				› Check <a href="http://regex101.com">regex101.com</a> for more.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	
	<div class="col-right">
		<h2>Search Hierarchy</h2>
		<p>Search methods have a hierarchy when combined:</p>
		<ol>
			<li><b>=exact=</b></li>
			<li><b>"phrase" / word</b></li>
			<li><b>#label</b></li>
		</ol>
		<p>RegEx searches have to start and end with a slash and can't be combined with anything else.</p>
